Date: Mon 24 Jan 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhuanet News Agency, Mon 24 Jan 2005 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-01/24/content_2500513.htm>

Viet Nam: 2 more human avian influenza cases reported
-----------------------------------------------
A 36-year-old man from Viet Nam's northern Thai Binh province has just been
found to have contracted avian influenza A (H5N1) virus, while a woman who
died on 21 Jan 2005 was confirmed to be infected with the virus, raising
the total number of bird flu infections in the country to 10.
Samples from the patient, who is receiving treatment at the Tropical
Disease Institute in Hanoi, tested positive for the H5N1 virus, the local
newspaper the Pioneer reported on Mon 24 Jan 2005, quoting Vietnamese
Deputy Minister of Health Tran Chi Liem. Earlier, samples from the
patient's brothers had also tested positive for the virus. The tests were
made by the National Hygiene and Epidemiology Institute. The 3 brothers ate
duck, and a dish made from raw duck blood, at a local market on 29 Dec
2004, before exhibiting symptoms of avian influenza. The 47-year-old
brother died on 9 Jan 2005 at the Tropical Disease Institute in Hanoi. The
42-year-old brother, who spent some time looking after his elder brother,
was admitted to the institute on 13 Jan 2005. The 36-year-old brother
received medical checkups at the institute last week [3rd week of January
2005]. The 36-year-old patient, who lives in Hanoi, and his younger
brother, who lives in Thai Binh, are now under treatment at the institute.
They are in stable condition.
The 35-year-old woman from southern Dong Thap province was admitted to the
Hospital of Tropical Disease in Ho Chi Minh City on 20 Jan 2005 and died on
the following day. She did not slaughter or eat sick or dead chickens, but
she often had a bath in a canal which contained dead fowl, her relatives said.
Among the 10 cases of avian influenza virus infection, 8 have died. Among
the dead, 7 were from the southern region and one from the northern region.
The 1st case in the [current] outbreak of avian influenza in Viet Nam was
reported on 28 Dec 2004. Since January 2005, avian influenza has stricken
404 communes of 25 cities and provinces nationwide, killing and leading to
the forced culling of more than 557 600 fowl, according to the Department
of Animal Health.
